article-doc.publication: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

p.link: Argentina unveiled a controversial plan aimed at preventing a default, while hinting it was willing to negotiate with holdout creditors.
Consumer prices rose 0.4% in May from April, the most in over a year, fueling debate over whether the Fed should move sooner to raise rates.
China blocked a tie-up of the world's three largest container-shipping firms, saying the alliance would control 47% of the Asia-to-Europe market.

article-body.p: U.S. stocks rose in light trading, led by small-company and financial shares. The Dow advanced 27.48 to 16808.49.
GE is considering the sale of its train-signaling business to Alstom as it bids for the French firm's energy assets.

p.link: Amazon.com is expected to reveal its first smartphone on Wednesday, with AT&T as the exclusive carrier.
Jefferies posted a 55% jump in profit, avoiding the headwinds that are slowing bigger Wall Street banks.
TD Ameritrade routinely sends customer orders to trading venues that pay the best, an executive told senators.
SunTrust settled allegations of abusive mortgage practices in a $968 million deal with the government.
The World Cup match between the U.S. and Ghana drew a record 15.9 million viewers on ESPN and Univision.
SolarCity agreed to buy Silevo, a maker of high-efficiency solar modules.
